Effect of Mood 
Similar to the original study, the replication found no significant effects of mood. There was no main effect of mood on attitudes toward prostitution F(59, 407) = 1.16, p = .208, ηp2  = 0.14. There was also no interaction between the writing condition and mood on attitudes toward prostitution F(40, 366) = 1.03, p = .428, ηp2  = 0.10. There was no main effect of mood on bail amounts F(59, 406) = 0.50, p = .999, ηp2  = 0.07. There was also no interaction between writing condition and mood on bail amounts F(40, 365) = 0.76, p = .861, ηp2  = 0.08.

Main Replication Test
	Unlike the original study, the interaction between culture and writing condition was not significant F(1, 433) = 1.12, p = .291, ηp2  = 0.003. (I’ll refer to the interaction between culture and writing condition on the Prostitution Attitude Scale as “the main replication test.”) 
	The patterns of the means were in the opposite direction from the original study. European Americans assigned to write about death were more positive toward prostitution (M = 1.37, SE = 0.15) than European Americans in the control condition (M = 1.27, SE = 0.13). East Asian participants assigned to write about death were more positive toward prostitution (M = 0.83, SE = 0.12) than participants in the control writing condition (M = 0.67, SE = 0.12).
	Following the original study, I tested the effect of writing in the two cultural groups separately. Among European American participants, the effect of writing was not significant F(1, 191) = 0.31, p = .578, ηp2  = 0.002. Among East Asian participants, the effect of writing was also not significant F(1, 242) = 0.94, p = .334, ηp2  = 0.004.
Similar to the original study, East Asian participants reported less positive attitudes toward prostitution than European American participants F(1, 221) = 6.15, p = .014, ηp2  = 0.03 (in the control condition). Looking at participants only in the experimental condition, results were similar. East Asian participants reported less positive attitudes toward prostitution than European American participants F(1, 212) = 13.88, p < .001, ηp2  = 0.06.

Bail Amounts
The main test for bail amounts was an interaction between culture and writing condition. This interaction was not significant F(1, 432) = 0.20, p = .654, ηp2  < 0.001. Similar to the results for attitudes, the means for bail were in the opposite direction from the original study. For European Americans, people who wrote about death made slightly lower bail demands (M = $229.01, SE = 28.98) than in the control condition (M = $270.33, SE = 31.72). For East Asian participants, people who wrote about death made higher bail demands (M = $5,285.81, SE = $4204.24) than in the control condition (M = $2,882.34, SE = 2456.94).
Next, I broke down the effect of the writing condition for each cultural group. Among participants in the control condition, cultural differences were not significant on the amount of bail set F(1, 221) = 0.94, p = .335, ηp2  = 0.004. Results were similar in the death-writing condition F(1, 211) = 1.10, p = .296, ηp2  = 0.01.

Limiting East Asian Sample to Participants Born in East Asia
	One possibility is that cultural differences would be larger if I compare European American participants to participants born in East Asia. However, the main replication effect was not significant when I limited the East Asian sample to participants born in East Asia (p = .834).

Analyzing Participants Who Wrote Two Sentences or More
	One problem with the data is that many participants wrote very little. For example, 12 participants wrote just one word. It is entirely possible that this poor compliance made our replication attempt dissimilar to the original. Although speculative, it is possible that the original study had better compliance because participants did the study in person, whereas our participants completed the study online. It’s possible that people feel less pressure to work hard on online studies and more pressure to work hard in person. 
To try to address the problem of writing few words, I collected more participants until I reached the planned sample size with participants who wrote 30 words or more. (This corresponds to two sentences or more, using one estimate of the average English sentence length of 15 words.) 
	It’s important to note one limitation of this design. Because the main reproducibility team did not allow me to add a word requirement in the survey (nor did they allow me to tell participants about how many words we wanted them to write), I was left with the participants that naturally wrote the required number of words. This resulted in highly unequal numbers of participants in the two conditions. Roughly twice as many people wrote 30 words about death (N = 93) than about dental pain (N = 49). 
One potential explanation is that people wrote more for death because thinking about bodily pain is more aversive than death. Although death is aversive, participants often wrote about philosophical aspects of death. One participant wondered what would happen to consciousness in the afterlife. Others mentioned memories of family or even curiosity. Yet with dental pain, participants had very little latitude to write. 
This aspect of the study design is worth noting because there could be selective attrition. For example, it may leave different types of participants leftover in the death condition and the dental pain condition. Studies have documented that this sort of selective attrition in supposedly random-assignment students can produce incorrect or even patently absurd results (Zhou & Fishbach, 2016). Thus, the results here should be taken with caution. 
	Results were similar when I analyzed participants who wrote 30 words or more. The main interaction between culture and writing condition did not reach significance F(1, 157) = 2.19, p = .141, ηp2  = 0.01. Similar to the main analysis, the means were in the opposite direction as the original study. For European Americans, writing about death made participants more positive toward prostitution (M = 1.56, SE = 0.18) than in the control condition (M = 1.32, SE = 0.21). For East Asian students, writing about death made participants less positive toward prostitution (M = 0.59, SE = 0.21) than in the control condition (M = 0.98, SE = 0.20).
	Results were similar for bail amount. The main interaction between culture and writing condition did not reach significance for bail F(1, 156) = 0.89, p = .346, ηp2  = 0.01. For European Americans, people who wrote about death made slightly lower bail demands (M = $198.70, SE = 36.30) than in the control condition (M = $285.28, SE = 88.50). For East Asian participants, people who wrote about death made higher bail demands (M = $12808.35, SE = 10571.74) than in the control condition (M = $311.15, SE = 55.45).

Outliers
	As planned, we scanned the main outcome variables (PAS scores) for outliers of more than two standard deviations. This revealed 20 outliers. All of the outliers were on the low side of the spectrum—with negative attitudes toward prostitution. However, after excluding these outliers, the main interaction effect remained non-significant (p = .410).

Skewed Bail Data
	The bail data included outliers over 2 SD. I re-ran the interaction between culture and writing condition after excluding outliers. The interaction remained non-significant (p = .630).
Even after excluding three participants with outlying bail data, the bail amount variable still far exceeded cutoffs of 2 for skewness and 7 for kurtosis (Curran et al., 1996). Square root transformation was not enough to reduce skewness and kurtosis. Log transformation was sufficient. After log transformation, the interaction remained non-significant (p = .980). Thus, the main null finding for bail amount was similar after correcting for skewness and outliers.

Excluding Prolific Participants
	To achieve the required sample size, I recruited a small number of participants through Prolific (N = 50), rather than the original university pool. Thus, I tested whether results were different after excluding Prolific participants. The main replication effect was similar after excluding Prolific participants (p = .194).

Religious Participants	
In an exploratory analysis, I tested whether religious participants would judge prostitution more harshly. I defined “religious” as any participant who identified with a religion. The non-religious were people who identified as “agnostic/do not identify” or “atheist.” Religious participants had less positive attitudes toward prostitution F(1, 468) = 22.03, p < .001, ηp2  = 0.05. 
	Perhaps not surprisingly, the effect of writing condition seemed to matter less among religious participants. This could happen if religious participants have more fixed attitudes toward prostitution (or perhaps have thought about death and the afterlife more often than non-religious participants). However, when I ran the main replication test among non-religious participants (N = 238), it remained non-significant F(1, 234) = 1.60, p = .207, ηp2  = 0.01. 

A Potential Explanation: COVID-19 Pandemic Is a Death Prime?
	Besides the methodological differences and deficiencies noted above, I offer one speculative explanation for the differences between the replication and the original study. All participants in this study completed the study during the COVID-19 pandemic. The earliest participants started in August, 2020. The last participants joined in the fall of 2021. Even during the fall of 2021, the United States was averaging over 1,000 deaths a day. This could change the effect of asking people to write about death. 
Unfortunately, we cannot test this speculative explanation in our data because all participants completed the study after the start of the pandemic. However, I offer this as a speculation worth considering for future research. 
